  <data name="Text_Geschiedenis" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The European Cup I (the original name is 'Coupe des Clubs Champions Européens', and still appears on the trophy) was the most important European club tournament in which the national champions of all UEFA member countries participated each season. Only in the early years were there some exceptions, including Dutch club PSV which participated in the 1955/56 season instead of Dutch champion Willem II. The trophy, which is still awarded to the winner of the Champions League, is also known as the "cup with the big ears". Those "big ears" are derived from the Greek/Roman amphora, whose handles served as carrying grips.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Text_Competitie" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The UEFA Champions League is the most important international football tournament for clubs in and around Europe. The tournament is organized by the European football association UEFA. The name Champions League has existed since 1992. Before that, the tournament was known as the European Cup I (also known as the UEFA Cup for national champions). Contrary to what the name suggests, it is a championship between top-finishing teams in national competitions, not just champions per country.</value>
  </data>
